<br>
The Faydark was as cheerful as ever. The birds chirped in the canopy above, and Elven voices carried far on the breeze. Kullgen stood with the other members of the Shadows, staring down the hill at the entrance to the Pale City of Felwithe, but her mind was farther south, and a week in the past.<br>
<br>
She could still hear Shintou's shouts echoing against the bark and in the loam. If she closed her eyes to focus, his face appeared before her, staring with empty eyes into her own. <br>
<br>
Kullgen stabbed her blade into the ground, and rubbed at her left wrist. He had clutched her hands not far from here as he clung to life, and she'd felt his Touch lance through her like cold fire. It wasn't the first Touch she'd taken, but it was the only of its kind she'd ever known. As she'd fallen to the ground, her eyes staring blankly, she'd felt hollow, barren. Where her own Hate had sat there was only a desolate coldness. She hadn't thought it possible, but ... <br>
<br>
&quot;Kullgen.&quot; She turned, blinking, to face Cora's scaled snout. &quot;The Priestesses are done with the blessings, and I've finished with my magicks. The Shadows are ready.&quot; She nodded, and pulled her sword from the earth. The Knight ignored the numbness in her left hand, and tightened her grip with the right. <br>
<br>
The League marched on the lands of the Light under her direction that day. Kullgen had hoped it would stir her, that seeing the blood flow from the children of Tunare and Brell would stoke her rage once more, and fill the steel void in her chest. Instead, as she swung at Elf, Dwarf, Human and runtling, her fury wouldn't come. She swung out of reflex rather than true malice, and her mind repeatedly strayed to the passionless face of the halfbreed that had at once inspired and stolen the Hate from her very soul.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kullgendphlith>Kullgen dPhlith</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.attbi.com/~subacca/spin.gif" BORDER=0> at: 4/14/03 1:47:31 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kullgendphlith>Kullgen dPhlith</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.attbi.com/~subacca/spin.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NOT A MAN</span><br>  Posts: 410<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/13/03 9:33:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=900.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~subacca/come_here.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Hollow Within</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>TWO</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
The numbness had gotten worse.<br>
<br>
The Knight couldn't tell, however, if its terrible coldness had spread up from the tingling in her left wrist, or down from the ache in her chest. Either way, her left arm was nearly useless, and she sat leaning against a withered tree in New Tanaan.<br>
<br>
She hadn't told Evariel. She couldn't summon the energy for the conversation, the questions it would bring. Once, she'd have hidden the wound from the Bonecaster to avoid seeing worry in her blue eyes, but now she stayed quiet out of weariness and apathy. Besides, it had been days since she'd seen her fiancee, who was studying and training hard at the Teir`dal outpost in Kunark. <br>
<br>
Kullgen refused to set foot near the cursed place. He was there, wasting his time on the Sarnaks. He, the one that had caused this pain, the one thing she could summon a morsel of emotion over. The only flickering of Hate left in her burned for the Knight, and kept her breathing. If only she were strong enough ... <br>
<br>
She tried flexing her hand, but watched in resignation as the fingers barely twitched. She'd never fell him in this state. Soon, if the spread of the cold ... <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>nothing</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> wasn't stopped, it would sprawl across her like a rash, a slithering weakness eating her from within. <br>
<br>
She wondered if he felt different since he'd sucked the Hate from her bones and left her shattered, or if not even her small infusion made any difference. Certainly, he was still wallowing in self-pity. No, no  - <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>meditating</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. The thought of her pain, her empty sacrifice wasted made her grit her teeth. <br>
<br>
Kullgen stood slowly, and staggered. The Hollow, as she had taken to calling it in her mind, was sliding down her ribs. Next her left leg would go, she figured. He was the key, she knew. Somehow ... if she were to beat him, crippled and wounded as she was, so far below his rank ... <br>
<br>
It was hopeless, but it was the only answer she could muster. With clenched jaw, and a weary sigh, she touched the Stone that led to the Overthere, intent on one answer or another. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kullgendphlith>Kullgen dPhlith</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.attbi.com/~subacca/spin.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NOT A MAN</span><br>  Posts: 411<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/14/03 1:44:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=900.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~subacca/come_here.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Hollow Within</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>THREE</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
The Kunark sun blasted down on her helm as she stalked about the Outpost. Sweat ran in streams down her temples and neck, and she called out once more.<br>
<br>
&quot;SHINAI!&quot;<br>
<br>
Nothing. For once, he wasn't near the outpost, and had left off his Sarnak genocide for the moment. She sighed. Once, she'd have cursed and struck out at a nearby rhino or walking cactus, but now she simply sighed. Her theory would go untested, it seemed, and she'd remain numb, crippled.<br>
<br>
The lightest touch to the pages of the book sent her back to New Tanaan, and she wandered aimlessly, mindlessly. As she neared the neutral center of the Plane, she saw him. For a moment, disappointment flared that she had come upon him in the peace-enforced city, but perhaps she'd have an answer after all.<br>
<br>
&quot;There you are.&quot; She stepped in front of him, and let her shield fall to her feet, baring her withered arm. <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, Kullgen?&quot; No malice. No anger. Nothing. He seemed as soulless as she felt. <br>
<br>
She only had one true question for him. &quot;Why? Why did you come that day in the Forest?&quot;<br>
<br>
They spoke in enforced civility for a time, and whether it was her apathy or his reasonings, she felt her last spark of Hate smother. The Hollow in her called out to the empty in his own soul, and for she found herself confiding in the halfbreed, and he seemed to understand.<br>
<br>
&quot;My passion,&quot; he intoned, &quot;was raped out of me by the neutralic machine. It died as I saw my dream burn away in their own blasts.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kullgen's eyes narrowed. &quot;At least your enemies are the ones that stole it from you. Mine was stabbed in the spine by someone I thought an ally.&quot; Perhaps Kaileena had taught him something after all, she mused.<br>
<br>
Shintou was uncomfortable speaking in the neutral section of the Plane, and she followed him to the Outpost. She told him of the effect of his Hand, the Touch he'd used on her, and how she could barely lift her blade. &quot;I'd thought,&quot; she muttered, &quot;that if I found you, and looked at you that at least my Hate would stir again, or at least I'd end the numbness on your blade. When I used my Touch on you, something was sucked from me, Shinai. When you reacted, and used yours, my flesh withered.&quot;<br>
<br>
He shruged at the puckered flesh of her arm. &quot;Maybe if we did it again, the Hatred would flow back within you? I've never known the Malious Hand to do that... I ... I'm sorry Kullgen. I don't know what to do.&quot;<br>
<br>
Not even now could she hate him. He hadn't intended it, and was as perplexed as she was. She leaned on her sword like an old woman's cane. &quot;All we can do is try. Either it will work, or it will end me. Either is preferable to this ... nothingness.&quot;<br>
<br>
Shintou sighed, and shook his head. &quot;I have a hard time hating you, Kullgen. I have no reason to.&quot;<br>
<br>
For the first time in a week, the Knight felt a slight bubble of emotion as she smirked. &quot;Since when does Shintou Shinai need a reason?&quot;<br>
<br>
They walked out of the sight of the over-zealous guards, and Shintou's fist began to glow a fierce, sickly green she'd seen before. Without another word, he struck, unleashing the Hate into her chest.<br>
<br>
The heat was unbearble. She burned from the inside out as her lifeblood splattered the halfbreed's face. Kullgen felt the twisting, searing pain shoot down her arms, her torso, her legs, and she fell to her knees. She lived, but was bleeding heavily.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well?&quot; The Knight demanded. <br>
<br>
&quot;It ... &quot; she croaked, unable to squeeze the other words out through her spasming throat. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>...burns oh Father it burns but it BURNS I feel it fire pain hatehatehate ... </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> She could smell the seared flesh of her chest and arms, and she looked up, her eyes blazing through her own blood. Her Hate had been returned even stronger, but at what cost?<br>
<br>
Shintou sneered at her. &quot;That one didn't even penetrate! Come now, surely you have more than that in you. Get up!&quot;<br>
Kullgen tried to push herself up, but fell back into the sand as her charred arms gave out under her. &quot;Worthless!&quot; he shouted. &quot;You let this halfbreed easily knock you to your knees.&quot; <br>
<br>
She rose up, staggering, under the power of her legs alone. Her shield and sword hung at her sides, limp. &quot;I can't ...&quot; she grunted, trying to move her arms and failing. &quot;I have only magicks - &quot; <br>
<br>
Kullgen threw herself against the Knight, and released the Hate that had so recently come back to her. He staggered a bit, but he was barely bruised. She tossed her weak Knight's spells at him, but did not, could not, strike with her weapon.<br>
<br>
Her magicks did little. &quot;You keep depending on those spells and you will get nowhere.&quot; He struck at her with his bare fists. &quot;Will yourself to move...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You're right,&quot; she muttered, casting another spear of disease. &quot;These spells are weak.&quot; She sat, and laid her useless arms in her lap.<br>
<br>
&quot;Kullgen - &quot;<br>
<br>
She looked up. &quot;But others are stronger.&quot; Kullgen bared her throat, and shook her head. &quot;If this body can't be healed, I'll find another way. Send me home, Elf.&quot; <br>
<br>
He nodded, but paused. &quot;You'll find your answers when you find where your Hate is directed.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You said it yourself, the Father is always watching. It all happens for a reason.&quot;<br>
<br>
With that, he ended her stay in the Outpost, and sent her soul screaming back to Neriak.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
