<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>They all staggered under the weight of her armor, but they carried her on. The merchants that found her, broken and charred, in the Foreign Quarter took her up and bore her to the Temple, to the High Priestess, before discarding her and returning to their duties.<br>
<br>
It wasn't the first time she'd been brought unconcious to the Priestess. Long ago, when she was but a young adult with a dagger and a sneaky disposition, she'd been brought here after dying at the hand of a human Paladin. She'd struck out in Hate at the man, and the Father had blessed her (cursed her? she often wondered) in that moment. <br>
<br>
Master Tolax told her once that he'd been awakened by the piercing, terrible voice of the Father, and told to retrieve her body, and to bring her to the Temple to be reborn in Hate. He had, and her life was given to the Lodge. Without them, she'd have died, and she served as much out of gratitude as obligation.<br>
<br>
But this time ... this time there was no one to speak for her, no one to guide the Priestess. She saw the Knight's burned flesh, and the muscles atrophied by pain. She saw the handprint seared into her chest, and the crisp skin that flaked around the shadowed fingers.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Harm Touch,&quot; <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>the healer mumbled, confused. She'd seen enough of them to recognize the signs, but she'd never seen ... this. The twisting of the muscles, as if they'd tried to wriggle out of her skin at the contact. The arms were twisted, pulled up with taut sinews, and the right hand was clamped around the hilt of a sword, still. <br>
<br>
The Knight lived, but she was deeply unconcious. The healer supposed that was for the best; those burns couldn't be pleasant. She sent a prayer to the Father, and set to her duties as best she could.<br>
<br>
Her mortal ears didn't hear what the nearly-dead Knight did: Innoruuk's hissing laughter. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
