<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Am I dead?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Kullgen wondered silently, floating amidst the gray nothingness. Finally, the pain was nowhere to be found, but neither was her body it seemed. She had no sense of up or down, had no head to move to check. There was nothing but gray waste, and her own whirling consciousness.<br>
<br>
The Void. So many cursed it each day without truly knowing of what they spoke. This terrible, unending nothing was horrifying, and she began to wonder if she'd prefer endless agony and suffering, as long as it was <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>something.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> As soon as the thought snaped across whatever her mind consisted of now, a dark spot began to pulse in front of her, throbbing in the gray. Had she eyes, she'd have wept for the sheer differentness of it, for the joy of something to focus on. <br>
<br>
The sphere began to grow, and a low hum emitted from its depths. The sound penetrated through Kullgen's being with a steady rhythm, almost like her missing heartbeat. The darkness, however, radiated a malevolence unmatched, and as her joy was replaced with horror, she realized it wasn't growing, but pulling her <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>into</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> it. She was overtaken, and blasted apart.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
<br>
Cold. It was the first thing she felt, and was immediately followed by &quot;hard&quot;. Kullgen opened an eye and found her face pressed into a rough stone floor. She lay on her left side, and was amazed to feel the cracks and bumps pressing into her arm, briefly grateful to feel anything at all. She planted her right palm against the floor, and eased herself up onto her feet.<br>
<br>
The room was sparsely lit, only a few guttering candles flickered before her, nestled together on a low wooden table nearby. They did little good. The shadows hung like drapes in the corners, and obscured the ceiling, making it impossible to judge the size of the chamber. Kullgen edged closer to the dim light; she was not alone.<br>
<br>
The presence was everywhere at once, behind her, to her sides, above her. It wasn't pleased. &quot;I know your thoughts, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Knight</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->,&quot; a rasping voice spat the words, and Kullgen felt a trill of panic race along her spine. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Oh no, no no no ...</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> &quot;I chose you.&quot;<br>
<br>
She fell to her knees without thought. &quot;Father, I - &quot;<br>
<br>
A soundless roar shook her bones. &quot;You do not speak.&quot; She nodded, tears streaming down her face. &quot;You failed me. Shintou Shinai is my pet, Child, and my tool. I use him, like I use all of you disgusting bags of filth. He was to raise your Hate, to force it out with his treachery and taunts. I sent him to the Faydark. I put the words in his mouth.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kullgen shook her head slightly, and opened her mouth to spew assurances. She was knocked backwards, and pinned to the floor by an unseen force at her throat. &quot;You think,&quot; the voice was close to her face, louder yet softer in tone, &quot;that you struck out at him in Hate? If only you were that strong.''<br>
The pressure on her throat eased, and she took a gasping breath. &quot;You fought out of fear. His words terrified you.&quot; <br>
<br>
She felt the truth between her ribs like claws. He was right, of course; Shintou's words of how the dark would never triumph against the soulless neutralic horde had chilled her, and she'd attacked him as a child wails to avoid a chore. She'd been horrified, because he voiced the same doubts she'd had, but he'd done it aloud, and in the face of their enemies. Kullgen had simply wanted to stop him from speaking, and had flown at him in fear.<br>
<br>
&quot;What do those pitiful fighters teach in the Lodge, Child? What is the first rule of the Knighthood, and of Neriak's people as a whole?&quot; She was afraid to speak, but the voice answered for her. &quot;Do. Not. Fear. You feared failure, and in so doing, failed. You disgust me, you false Knight.&quot; <br>
<br>
She was lifted by the throat by the unseen hand, and held aloft with her toes barely grazing the soild floor. &quot;It wasn't Shintou that Touched you, girl. It was me. I withered that body, I sapped you of your fighting strength to punish you.&quot; Kullgen fell into a crumpled heap, weeping.<br>
<br>
&quot;You are a Knight no longer, but you are still my servant. I am not through with you yet. Even after death, your shriveled corpse will dance at my hand. You will spread my Hate, and be forced to walk among the whole as a crippled reminder of the price of failure.&quot; <br>
<br>
The shadows streaked towards her until she was engulfed once more in the Void, but the voice sounded in the nothing one last time.<br>
<br>
&quot;You live yet, Bonecaster.&quot;<br>
