<br>
While no bards would sing the tale in musty, smoky taverns, and no historian would spend her days studying each blow, to Kullgen the battle was epic. Some of the blood soaking into the earth was her foe's, but most was her own. Leaning heavily on her staff and panting, the apprentice stood triumphant over the corpse of the black wolf.<br>
<br>
After she'd caught her breath, and bound her wounds tightly, she knelt, wincing, and drew her knife. She made short work of the skinning; her right hand was still as deft and sure as it had ever been. She dragged herself to her feet once more, and staggered back to the welcome shadow of Neriak's entrance, her left foot leaving a snake's trail behind her in the dirt.<br>
<br>
The wall was cool against her cheek, and she debated sitting down. Rising was such a chore now with her traitorous leg and arm, but standing wasn't very much better. Carefully, and with agonizing slowness, she slid down the wall, and closed her eyes.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;You cannot leave yet,&quot; the Priestess warned. &quot;You are not strong enough, and we have much more work to do on that leg.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kullgen pushed herself onto her feet, clutching the bed for stability. Her eyes blazed. She could see the pity in the woman's eyes, the disgust at her deformed arm and scarred, stretched skin. She'd seen it for days, ever since she'd woken to the steel brush scouring the burnt flesh. Kullgen's throat still ached from the screaming.<br>
<br>
&quot;The only way I'm staying another minute in this stinking, festering room is if you kill me.&quot; She snatched a dark robe from the back of a nearby chair, and covered herself. The sleeves were long enough that they hid her twisted left arm, and Kullgen was grateful. She couldn't bear to see it.<br>
<br>
The Priestess threw up her hands. &quot;Fine. Go. But if I find you here again because you've fallen, or made your wounds worse because of your pride, I'll let you rot.&quot; The woman tossed a dark staff at Kullgen. It had a skull mounted atop it, and the eye sockets gleamed. &quot;Master Tolax brought that by. You'll need it.&quot;<br>
<br>
The staff clattered to the ground, and Kullgen glared at the healer's retreating back. The blow to her ego was tremendous. Once able to nimbly dodge and feint, now she couldn't even catch a stick, and bending over to retrieve it seemed tantamount to swimming the Timorous Deep with bricks tied to her legs. <br>
<br>
She couldn't, however, walk without support, and she bent at the knees trying to get closer to the grinning skull. Kullgen had to let go of the bed to grasp at the staff, and for a brief moment her fingers grazed the wood and bone. She clutched desperately, lost her balance, and tipped over onto her side.<br>
<br>
Kullgen lay there for what seemed hours, clenching her jaw and fighting back tears of rage and frustration. She stared into the empty eyesockets of the face, and wondered if it felt as helpless as she did.<br>
<br>
She had fallen on her right side, her good side, and had to roll to her stomach to free her arm. Thankfully, her better half was still strong - a painful reminder of her former power - and she was able to push herself to her knees and snatch up the staff. With a lot of cursing, Kullgen pulled herself to her feet, and wondered how she was supposed to live in this shell. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The cold stone was seeping into her joints, and Kullgen knew if she didn't get up now, she'd face even more pain later. A passing young enchanter stopped to offer her a hand, but a snarl and a few choice epithets send him fleeing.<br>
<br>
If she couldn't do it alone, she wouldn't do it at all.<br>
<br>
