<br>
The trek took ages. Kullgen had to stop often and rest against a tree, panting, but in the end she finally passed into the East Commonlands. She had to train close to home, now, since travelling was so much more difficult. As a young Knight she'd trotted off all around the world seeking new sights and new foes, but she'd never set foot in the Commonlands. <br>
<br>
Her eyes burned in the glare of the sun, and she was momentarily blinded as she stepped from the damp shade of Nektulos forest. As her vision adjusted, she called a minion to her for whatever protection it would offer. Joner swayed at her side, waiting patiently for her to collect herself, and after a short rest they followed the worn path out into the hills. <br>
<br>
&quot;Kullgen?&quot; <br>
<br>
The bonecaster turned, and found herself face to face with the crimson eyes of Kailena. She gestured a greeting, and flicked a glance down to her dead arm, making sure it was covered. &quot;Hello, Kailena. Your hunt goes well, I hope.&quot; <br>
<br>
The young Knight nodded. She was fresh to her power, having recently been called to the Father's service. For a moment, Kullgen wondered if the universe could only take a fixed number of unholy Knights, and for every new one that is born, another must die.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm glad to see you,&quot; Kailena said with a sigh. &quot;I wanted to ask you about this sword - &quot; <br>
<br>
Kullgen's shoulders tensed. &quot;I'm not the one to ask any longer. Seek out Tallonar.&quot; Her voice was flat, but her palm itched to hold the blade's hilt. <br>
<br>
The Knight blinked, and nodded. &quot;Yes, I'd heard rumor in the Halls but ... is it true?&quot; She peered at the scarred side of Kullgen's neck, and at the misshapen lump under the sleeve. &quot;Did Shintou do that?&quot; <br>
<br>
A snort burst from Kullgen, and she shook her head, turning the melted skin from view. &quot;He was the vessel, but it was not him. I'm sure he'd like to think it was, but this was the work of the Father.&quot; She swallowed, and leaned on her staff. &quot;I'd rather not speak of it now.&quot; <br>
<br>
After deciding they'd be much more deadly together, Kullgen let Kailena lead. The Knight was familiar with the area, and they were soon looking down at a small camp of orcs, Deathfists by the cut of their tunics. &quot;We must wait for one to wander off,&quot; Kullgen advised, but Kailena disagreed, grinning at her sword. <br>
<br>
&quot;We can handle them. This new strength of mine is more than match for those green bastards.&quot; She flicked a bit of dried blood from her armor, and sighed happily. &quot;It's amazing. I feel like a completely new woman.&quot; <br>
<br>
Kullgen's hand tightened on her staff. &quot;I know the feeling.&quot; <br>
<br>
Kailena pointed to the nearest orc; he stood near the edge of the camp, and might come alone if his cries weren't too loud. &quot;Get ready,&quot; she warned, and shot an arrow into the creature's leg. He wailed in pain before limping up the hill, and two of his fellow Legionnaires followed. <br>
<br>
&quot;The more the merrier,&quot; Kailena cackled as she swung, her blade slicing into the stomach of her first attacker. Kullgen sent Joner in to help, and muttered a few incantations. One, and then another orc fell, and Kailena was hacking at the last when it suddenly exploded at the chest. Both women were covered in Orc gore, and Kailena wiped her face. &quot;That always feels so, so good.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kailena had Touched the Orc, just to feel the pleasure of the Father's power course through her, and Kullgen blinked. The pain of her loss seared through her, as fresh as ever. She could feel the empty hollow in her chest throb, where the power had rested, and she had to breathe deeply to stop her head from swimming.<br>
<br>
Her mourning was interrupted by the slash of claws in her back, and Kailena's warning cry, &quot;Get back!&quot; It was a kodiak, and the Knight lept between its teeth and Kullgen's thin robes. Kullgen staggered back, once again reminded of her physical weakness, and something within the Bonecaster burst. <br>
<br>
She watched the new Knight swing and feint, dodge and bash, with great interest. Heat flared low in her belly, and spread up, licking at her cheeks. Her breath came faster through parted lips, and with a slight gesture she called Joner back to her side, leaving Kailena to fight the bear alone. <br>
<br>
Kullgen's eyes blazed as the Knight took a nasty swipe to the leg, and began bleeding heavily. The scent of blood made the Bonecaster's nostrils flare, and she bit her bottom lip in anticipation. Though Kailena was wounding the bear severely, her own life was ebbing faster and faster. As she crumpled to the ground, unconscious, Kullgen traced a glyph in the air with shaking fingers, and drained the bear's remaining life and healed her own wounds. <br>
<br>
She leaned over the dying woman, and her smile would have frozen the heart of anyone passing. &quot;Who is powerful now?&quot; she asked the air, and knelt slowly. She dipped her fingers in the wound at Kailena's thigh, and brought them to her lips. &quot;Are you afraid?&quot; she whispered, fighting back a manic giggle, and watched as the woman's skin turned from deep, glowing blue to a dusky slate. <br>
<br>
She leaned over the barely living body. Kullgen wanted to see the life exit from the Knight's eyes. As she moved, however, the Common's sun glinted off the silver badge upon Kailena's chest, and the flash was ice water on Kullgen's hate-fevered brain. She gasped, and shook her head, trying to clear the remaining fog. Kailena was League, and an ally; she couldn't let her die. Kullgen ripped off the hem of her gown and tied the gushing wound tightly. Se cried out the words to drain her own life and replace Kailena's, and after a few chantings, the Knight was awake, but still gravely wounded. <br>
<br>
If Kailena had heard Kullgen's words, or had any suspicion, she hid it well. Kullgen's grim face was easily mistaken for worry, and she made no move to explain otherwise.<br>
<br>
&quot;That was close,&quot; Kailena groaned, and Kullgen nodded absently. For the first time since her punishment, she felt strong. Not in body, of course; a stiff wind could shatter her tormented bones. She was strong in mind. She was strong in will. <br>
<br>
She was strong in Hate. <br>
<br>
